scenarioDescription:
The TrES-5 Exoplanetary System


Overview

TrES-5 is a star with 0.9 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.87 times its radius. It is located 1187.53 light years away from the solar system.

TrES-5 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the TrES-5 system


TrES-5 b

TrES-5 b was discovered by the TrES observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.02 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of TrES-5 b is 569.22 times the mass of Earth. The radius of TrES-5 b is 13.384 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, TrES-5 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
